04495nam a22007215i 9780674033887DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740338877 a10.4159/97806740338872doi  a(DE-B1597)567752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBF720.S63bR43 2008 7aMED1050102bisacsh04a155.42/2822221 aReddy, Vasudevi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Infants Know Minds /cVasudevi Reddy. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. A Puzzle -- t2. Minding the Gap -- t3. Engaging Minds: A Second-Person Approach -- t4. Making Contact: Imitation -- t5. Opening Conversations -- t6. Experiencing Attention -- t7. Feeling Self-Conscious -- t8. Playing with Intentions -- t9. Sharing Funniness -- t10. Faking in Communication -- t11. Other Minds and Other Cultures -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Most psychologists claim that we begin to develop a “theory of mind”—some basic ideas about other people’s minds—at age two or three, by inference, deduction, and logical reasoning. But does this mean that small babies are unaware of minds? That they see other people simply as another (rather dynamic and noisy) kind of object? This is a common view in developmental psychology. Yet, as this book explains, there is compelling evidence that babies in the first year of life can tease, pretend, feel self-conscious, and joke with people. Using observations from infants’ everyday interactions with their families, Vasudevi Reddy argues that such early emotional engagements show infants’ growing awareness of other people’s attention, expectations, and intentions. Reddy deals with the persistent problem of “other minds” by proposing a “second-person” solution: we know other minds if we can respond to them. And we respond most richly in engagement with them. She challenges psychology’s traditional “detached” stance toward understanding people, arguing that the most fundamental way of knowing minds—both for babies and for adults—is through engagement with them. According to this argument the starting point for understanding other minds is not isolation and ignorance but emotional relation."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCognition in infants. 0aInfant psychology. 0aInterpersonal relations in children. 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge). 0aSocial interaction in infants. 0aSocial perception in children. 7aMEDICAL / Psychiatry / Child & Adolescent.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674033887zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674033887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674033887/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK